            <h1>Clinical Guidelines for Neonatal Jaundice (AAP 2022 & NICE CG98)</h1>
        </div>
        
        <div class="hd-meta">
            <strong>References:</strong> 
            <ul>
                <li>Kemper AR, et al. "Clinical Practice Guideline Revision: Management of Hyperbilirubinemia in the Newborn Infant 35 or More Weeks of Gestation." <em>Pediatrics.</em> 2022;150(3):e2022058859.</li>
                <li>NICE Clinical Guideline [CG98]. "Jaundice in newborn babies under 28 days." Updated October 2023.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- 1. Scope of Application -->
        <section class="hd-section">
            <h2>1. Scope of Application (Dual Protocol)</h2>
            <p>The system combines two leading clinical guidelines (US and UK) to provide the safest guidance for infants:</p>
            <ul class="hd-list">
                <li><strong>AAP 2022:</strong> Applies to newborn infants <strong>≥ 35 weeks gestation</strong> and up to <strong>336 hours (14 days after birth)</strong>.</li>
                <li><strong>NICE CG98:</strong> Applies to newborn infants <strong>up to 672 hours (28 days after birth)</strong>, supporting preterm infants and calculating exact thresholds via interpolation.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><em>Safety Principle of BiliTool.Vn: The algorithm calculates thresholds under both guidelines and automatically recommends the lower (stricter) treatment threshold.</em></p>
        </section>

        <!-- 2. Risk Assessment -->
        <section class="hd-section">
            <h2>2. Risk Factor Assessment</h2>
            
            <h3 class="mt-3" style="color: #2563eb;"><i class="fas fa-brain"></i> Neurotoxicity Risk Factors (AAP 2022)</h3>
            <p>If <strong>ANY</strong> of these factors are present, the treatment threshold is automatically lowered:</p>
            <ul class="hd-list">
                <li><strong>Isoimmune hemolytic disease:</strong> ABO, Rh incompatibility, positive DAT (Coombs test).</li>
                <li><strong>G6PD deficiency</strong> or other hemolytic disorders.</li>
                <li><strong>Sepsis:</strong> Confirmed or suspected.</li>
                <li><strong>Clinical instability:</strong> Shock, mechanical ventilation, asphyxia... in the past 24 hours.</li>
                <li><strong>Low serum albumin:</strong> &lt; 3.0 g/dL.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><em>Note: Prematurity (35 - 37 weeks) is NOT marked as a risk factor here, as it is handled by separate gestational age curves.</em></p>

            <h3 class="mt-4" style="color: #059669;"><i class="fas fa-notes-medical"></i> Clinical Risk Factors (NICE CG98)</h3>
            <ul class="hd-list">
                <li><strong>Jaundice visible within 24h:</strong> Red flag, monitor closely.</li>
                <li><strong>Hemolytic disease (Rh/ABO):</strong> Assess for IVIG if TSB increases &gt; 8.5 µmol/L/hour.</li>
                <li><strong>Kernicterus Risk:</strong> Emergency warning if TSB &gt; 340 µmol/L (for infants ≥37w), or increases &gt; 8.5 µmol/L/hour, or acute encephalopathy signs.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- 3. Intervention Thresholds -->
        <section class="hd-section">
            <h2>3. Clinical Intervention Thresholds</h2>
            <ul class="hd-list">
                <li><strong>Phototherapy Threshold:</strong> TSB level to initiate blue light phototherapy.</li>
                <li>
                    <strong style="color: #c0392b;">Intensive Phototherapy (Escalation of Care):</strong> Indicated when TSB reaches:
                    <ul>
                        <li>AAP 2022: TSB is within <strong>2.0 mg/dL</strong> of the exchange transfusion threshold.</li>
                        <li>NICE CG98: TSB is within <strong>50 µmol/L</strong> (~2.9 mg/dL) of the exchange transfusion threshold.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong style="color: #8e1010;">Exchange Transfusion:</strong> Urgent exchange transfusion if TSB reaches threshold or infant shows signs of acute bilirubin encephalopathy.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- 4. NICE CG98 Specific Recommendations -->
        <section class="hd-section">
            <h2>4. NICE CG98 Specific Recommendations</h2>
            <ul class="hd-list">
                <li><strong>Stopping phototherapy:</strong> Consider stopping once TSB falls <strong>≥ 50 µmol/L</strong> below the phototherapy threshold.</li>
                <li><strong>Rebound check:</strong> Repeat bilirubin measurement <strong>12 - 18 hours</strong> after stopping phototherapy to check for rebound.</li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Prolonged Jaundice:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Term infants (≥ 37w): Jaundice lasting <strong>&gt; 14 days</strong>.</li>
                        <li>Preterm infants (&lt; 37w): Jaundice lasting <strong>&gt; 21 days</strong>.</li>
                        <li><em>Recommendation:</em> Test conjugated bilirubin, FBC, blood group, DAT, and screen for metabolic/thyroid disorders.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>IVIG Indication:</strong> Administer IVIG 500 mg/kg over 4 hours if Rh/ABO hemolytic disease is present AND TSB increases &gt; 8.5 µmol/L/hour.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

